1. A sample wraps an integer in the range 0 to 1000 and a label string up to 32 characters long.
2. A token is one of three kinds: a name-carrying identifier, an integer literal, or an end-of-input sentinel.
3. To classify a sample: if the integer is 0 it is an identifier carrying the sample's label; if it is strictly greater than 100 it is end-of-input; otherwise it is an integer literal carrying the integer.
4. To label a sample: classify it; if the result is an identifier produce "id:" followed by the carried name; if it is an integer literal produce "int:" followed by the carried number; if it is end-of-input produce "eof".
